            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Some conclusions I feel reasonably certain of (corrections welcome):\r\n\r\n1. Vim timers behave like JS `setTimeout`; Nvim timers behave like JS `setInterval`. [Reference](https://stackoverflow.com/a/729943/152142)\r\n2.. Most developers would not expect/want the expected frequency to be cut in half, as in **1a**.\r\n    - In that case, Nvim behavior may be slightly more intuitive.\r\n3. *Pause behavior:* programmer expects only one thing:  the timer _doesn't trigger during the pause increment._ Anything else is details.\r\n4. The Vim documentation is worded in such a way to make it clear that developers should not expect any predictable behavior at all. So we aren't really bound to any particular behavior.\r\n\r\n(3) gives us wiggle-room. The ideal solution would be to behave like Vim, but add a `timer_start()` option that changes the behavior, so that we have _both_ `setTimeout` and `setInterval`.\r\n\r\nMost likely, though, no one cares. Anyone who _does_ care must [\"self modify\"](https://stackoverflow.com/a/729943/152142) by recreating the timer with an adjusted increment (in Vim or Nvim) to have any hope of predictability.\r\n\r\nSuggested actions:\r\n\r\n- [ ] Adjust docs if needed, but definitely include your nice (Nvim) diagrams. \r\n- [ ] Adjust tests.\r\n- [ ] Create a new issue in **unplanned** milestone to implement the `timer_start()` optional behavior mentioned above. This is probably more trouble than it is worth.",
